---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Disclosure from '../../components/Disclosure.astro';
import EmailCapture from '../../components/EmailCapture.astro';
import { url } from '../../utils/url';

const cost = [
  { item: 'Tank + stand (75g, 48×18×21″)', budget: '$350–550', mid: '$550–1,000' },
  { item: 'Sump (20-long / 29g or purpose-built)', budget: '$100–180', mid: '$180–450' },
  { item: 'Return pump (~525 GPH at the tank)', budget: '$80–140', mid: '$140–250' },
  { item: 'Protein skimmer', budget: '$150–250', mid: '$250–500' },
  { item: 'Reef lighting (2 fixtures across 48″)', budget: '$400–700', mid: '$700–1,400' },
  { item: 'Powerheads / flow', budget: '$120–220', mid: '$220–450' },
  { item: 'Heater(s) ~250–300W + controller', budget: '$50–90', mid: '$90–180' },
  { item: 'Rock (~50–75 lb) + sand (~70 lb)', budget: '$120–220', mid: '$220–380' },
  { item: 'RODI unit', budget: '$80–150', mid: '$150–250' },
  { item: 'Salt, test kits, extras', budget: '$90–160', mid: '$160–300' },
];
---
<Base
  title="75 Gallon Reef Tank Setup Guide, Gear List & Cost"
  description="The complete 75-gallon reef tank setup: why it's the hobby's sweet spot, the exact gear list with honest sizing, a realistic 2026 cost breakdown, and calculators to size the pump, skimmer, and flow for your build."
  breadcrumbs={[{ name: 'Guides', href: '/guides' }, { name: '75 Gallon Reef Setup', href: '/guides/75-gallon-reef-tank-setup' }]}
>
  <section class="container prose" style="padding-top:40px;">
    <p class="eyebrow" style="color:var(--brand-2)">Setup guide</p>
    <h1>75 Gallon Reef Tank: Setup, Gear List &amp; Cost</h1>
    <p class="lede-dark">Ask experienced reefers what tank they'd buy again and the 75 comes up more than anything else. Four feet long, a real 18 inches front-to-back, and enough water volume that your parameters stop swinging at every mistake. Here's the full build — with each piece sized for <em>this</em> tank, not copied off a generic list.</p>

    <Disclosure />

    <h2>Why the 75 is the sweet spot</h2>
    <p>At 48 × 18 × 21 inches, the 75 fixes the two things that quietly ruin smaller "starter" tanks: it has the same 18-inch front-to-back depth as the 40 breeder (so aquascaping actually works), and it stretches it across a four-foot length that fits standard lighting and gives fish real swimming room. The extra volume is stability you can't buy any other way — evaporation, temperature, and alkalinity all drift slower in 75 gallons than in 40. It's also the largest common size that still fits through a doorway on two people's arms.</p>

    <h2>Know your real volume first</h2>
    <p>A "75" doesn't hold 75 gallons — after the sand, rock, and air gap it typically sees the mid-60s, plus whatever's in the sump. Every dose and stocking decision downstream keys off that number, so pin it down first: <a href={url('/tools/tank-volume-calculator')} class="inlinecta">→ get your true water volume</a> (the 75 is a preset).</p>

    <h2>The core gear list</h2>

    <h3>Sump + return pump</h3>
    <p>At this size a sump stops being optional-but-nice and becomes the default — it hides the heater and skimmer, adds 15–25 gallons of stabilizing volume, and makes an ATO trivial. A 20-long fits almost any 75 stand; a 29 fits most. For the return, aim for roughly <strong>7× display turnover at the tank</strong> — about 525 GPH <em>delivered</em>, which after head loss usually means a pump rated well above that. Don't guess what your plumbing eats:</p>
    <p><a href={url('/tools/return-pump-calculator')} class="inlinecta">→ Size your return pump with the calculator</a></p>
    <p style="margin-top:-6px;"><a href={url('/reviews/best-return-pumps')}>See our full return pump rankings →</a></p>

    <h3>Protein skimmer</h3>
    <p>Manufacturer ratings assume a lightly-stocked tank. A 75 with a normal fish load wants a skimmer honestly rated for it after derating — which knocks out several models whose box says "up to 100 gallons":</p>
    <p><a href={url('/tools/protein-skimmer-calculator')} class="inlinecta">→ Find the right skimmer for your bioload</a></p>
    <p style="margin-top:-6px;"><a href={url('/reviews/best-protein-skimmers')}>See our full protein skimmer rankings →</a></p>

    <h3>Lighting</h3>
    <p>Four feet of tank means <strong>two fixtures</strong> for even coverage — a single centered light leaves the ends dim enough to matter. Softies and LPS are fine under two mid-range LEDs; SPS across a 48-inch tank is where lighting becomes the biggest line in the budget. Before you spend $700+ on marketing claims: <a href={url('/reviews/best-reef-led-lighting')}>only 4 of the 11 popular fixtures we compared publish verifiable PAR data</a> — buy from those four.</p>

    <h3>Flow</h3>
    <p>Total flow (return + powerheads) should land around <strong>20–40× turnover</strong> for a mixed reef — 1,500–3,000 GPH in a 75 — higher for SPS-dominant. Two powerheads on opposite ends beat one big one: you want chaotic, colliding flow, not a laminar river. <a href={url('/tools/flow-calculator')}>Work out your target and see which wavemakers hit it →</a></p>

    <h3>Heat</h3>
    <p>Plan on <strong>250–300W</strong> total — ideally as two smaller heaters instead of one, so a stuck-on failure (the classic heater death) can only cook half as fast, and a stuck-off one still leaves you half your heat. Put them on an external controller regardless; the built-in thermostat is the part that fails. <a href={url('/tools/heater-calculator')}>Size it for your room temperature →</a></p>

    <h3>Rock + sand</h3>
    <p>Modern minimal scapes run <strong>50–75 lb of rock</strong> in a 75 — enough biological surface without filling the swim space. Sand: a 1–1.5″ bed over the 48×18 footprint is about <strong>70–90 lb</strong> (the <a href={url('/tools/tank-volume-calculator')}>volume calculator</a> computes it for your exact depth).</p>

    <h2>What a 75 build actually costs</h2>
    <p>Two honest columns — value and mid-range, 2026 US prices. Lighting is the swing item: it's nearly a third of the mid-range total because covering four feet properly takes two real fixtures. Use <a href={url('/tools/reef-build-cost-calculator')}>the build cost calculator</a> to itemize your own tier, and <a href={url('/reviews/best-reef-salt-mix')}>the salt rankings</a> for the biggest recurring line.</p>

    <table class="costtable">
      <thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Value build</th><th>Mid-range</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        {cost.map((c) => (<tr><td>{c.item}</td><td>{c.budget}</td><td>{c.mid}</td></tr>))}
      </tbody>
      <tfoot><tr><td><strong>Rough total</strong></td><td><strong>~$1,500–2,700</strong></td><td><strong>~$2,700–5,200</strong></td></tr></tfoot>
    </table>
    <p class="rnote">Ranges, not quotes — prices move with sales. You also don't buy it all at once: tank, stand, sump, RODI, and rock come first; the skimmer can arrive during the cycle; corals come months in.</p>

    <h2>Stocking a 75</h2>
    <p>This is the size where the "sorry, tank's too small" list gets short. A 75 comfortably runs a pair of clowns, a yellow or purple tang, a wrasse or two, a royal gramma, and a goby/pistol pair with room left over. It's still not a home for hippo tangs or most triggers — but for the first time, most of the fish at the LFS are actually on the table.</p>

    <h2>The order of operations</h2>
    <p>Set the tank and plumb the sump → run RODI and mix saltwater → aquascape the rock → start the pump, skimmer, and heater → cycle (2–6 weeks) → cleanup crew → fish, then corals, slowly. The 75's volume forgives a lot, but it doesn't forgive rushing the cycle.</p>

    <h2>Other sizes</h2>
    <p>Smaller room or budget? <a href={url('/guides/40-gallon-breeder-reef-tank-setup')}>The 40 breeder</a> keeps the same footprint depth at half the water. Considering the 55 you saw on sale? <a href={url('/guides/55-gallon-reef-tank-setup')}>Read this first</a> — its 13-inch width is a real problem the price tag doesn't mention. Going bigger: <a href={url('/guides/120-gallon-reef-tank-setup')}>the 120</a> adds a second foot of depth that changes aquascaping completely.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="container">
    <EmailCapture />
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .lede-dark { margin-bottom: 8px; }
